name: Sarah Gorby
comments: Born in Kishinev (Chisinau), then part of Tsarist Russia, now capital of Moldova. She left Kishinev at age 17 to study music in Iași, Romania, where she married Joseph Goldstein. She moved to Rome and then to Paris in the 1920s, but returned to Iași every summer until the outbreak of World War II to visit her husband. She also toured South America regularly during the 1930s. For a time in the 1930's she performed with her husband's last name (Sarah Goldstein) before switching to the stage name Sarah Gorby. In 1940 she and her husband emigrated to Haiti and Gorby continued on to the United States. Around 1949, she returned to Paris; upon her husband's death in Haiti in the 1950 she settled permanently in Paris. After settling in Paris she recorded quite a lot under the label Eledisc, which was then releasing many Yiddish language singers.

name: Irene West
comments: Dancer, vaudeville and revue impresario, artist manager, night club and theater owner and manager, born in Dallas, Texas. She began her career as a dancer at the age of 17. She spent much of her life living in Honolulu and became best known for popularizing Hawaiian music in the United States and around the world. In particular, she managed a troupe of Hawaiian singers and musicians who provided music for Richard Walton Tully's play, "The Bird of Paradise," which opened at the Belasco Theater in Los Angeles on Sept. 11, 1911. It opened on Broadway at New York City’s Daly’s Theatre on January 8, 1912. This highly successful show and its music triggered wide-spread interest in Hawaiian music. Irene West's groups made pioneering recordings of Hawaiian music which were followed by many recording by other artists. Her group included skilled guitar and steel guitar players who influenced many artists who recorded later.
